#Value that appeared most frequently in daily.time.spent.on.site
getmode<-function(v){
  uniqv<-unique(v)
  uniqv[which.max(tabulate(match(v,uniqv)))]
}

Covariance

# Assigning the Daily.Time.Spent.on.Site column to the variable dailt_time
daily_time <- numeric_cols$Daily.Time.Spent.on.Site
# Assigning the Age column to the variable waiting
age<- numeric_cols$Age
# Using the cov() function to determine the age
cov(daily_time, age)
## [1] -46.17415

the covariance relationship between Daily time spent on site and Age is -46.17415 indicating a negative linear relationship between the two variables

# Assigning the Clicked.on.Ad column to the variable Ad_clicked

Modeling

Decision Trees

library(caret)
## Loading required package: lattice
library(DescTools)
## 
## Attaching package: 'DescTools'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:caret':
## 
##     MAE, RMSE
library(rpart)
library(rpart.plot)

Partationing the data

set.seed(12345)
partition <- createDataPartition(y = numeric_cols$Clicked.on.Ad, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
oj.train <- numeric_cols[partition, ]
oj.test <- numeric_cols[-partition, ]
rm(partition)
set.seed(123)
oj.full_class <- rpart(formula = Clicked.on.Ad ~ .,
                       data = oj.train,
                       method = "class",  # classification (not regression)
                       xval = 10  # 10-fold cross-validation 
                       )
rpart.plot(oj.full_class, yesno = TRUE)

printcp(oj.full_class)
## 
## Classification tree:
## rpart(formula = Clicked.on.Ad ~ ., data = oj.train, method = "class", 
##     xval = 10)
## 
## Variables actually used in tree construction:
## [1] Area.Income              Daily.Internet.Usage     Daily.Time.Spent.on.Site
## 
## Root node error: 400/800 = 0.5
## 
## n= 800 
## 
##      CP nsplit rel error xerror     xstd
## 1 0.795      0     1.000 1.0850 0.035227
## 2 0.065      1     0.205 0.2150 0.021902
## 3 0.020      2     0.140 0.1575 0.019046
## 4 0.010      4     0.100 0.1375 0.017892
#Prunning the tree
oj.class <- prune(oj.full_class, 
                  cp = oj.full_class$cptable[which.min(oj.full_class$cptable[, "xerror"]), "CP"])
rm(oj.full_class)
rpart.plot(oj.class, yesno = TRUE)

plotcp(oj.class)

#Prediction
oj.class.pred <- predict(oj.class, oj.test, type = "class")
plot(oj.test$Clicked.on.Ad, oj.class.pred, 
     main = "Simple Classification: Predicted vs. Actual",
     xlab = "Actual",
     ylab = "Predicted")

Conclusion

  • the daily time spent on site was not directly proportional to the number of Ads clicked
  • Age determined a lot the number of clicked ads. Aged people clicked more Ads
  • Daily internet used was not directly proportional with the number of clicked Ads

Recommendation

  • The types of Ads should be made relevasnce to all age groups in order to attract more people to click them.
